transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello, and thank you for having me. I'm ready to answer your questions and share my experiences. Please go ahead.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Sure! As I mentioned, my name is Mia, and I’m 29 years old. I live in a rural part of Arkansas with my husband. I work as an administrative assistant, but my hours have been pretty inconsistent lately, which has made things a bit challenging financially. I graduated high school, but I haven’t pursued any further education. 

We live in a small house that isn’t in the best condition, and I sometimes feel isolated because I don’t have a lot of social contacts nearby. I have one child who’s two years old now, and my delivery went smoothly. Right now, I’m not planning to have more kids, and I use condoms for contraception. Overall, I try to manage, but sometimes it feels tough, especially with healthcare access being limited.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I found out I was pregnant about three years ago. I remember feeling a mix of excitement and nervousness. It was a bit of a surprise since we weren't actively trying to conceive. I took a home pregnancy test, and when it was positive, I just sat there for a moment, taking it all in. 

My pregnancy was pretty straightforward, and I had regular check-ups. I was fortunate that everything went smoothly, and I had an uncomplicated vaginal delivery two years ago. The staff at the hospital were really kind and supportive, which made the experience a lot easier. After my son was born, I felt a bit overwhelmed, but I was also really happy. 

After having him, I made the decision not to have more children right now, and that’s why I use condoms for contraception. I just want to focus on my current family and make sure we’re all doing well.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I first sought prenatal care as soon as I found out I was pregnant, which was around the sixth week of my pregnancy. I was really eager to start seeing a doctor and make sure everything was going well. I went to a local clinic that was a bit of a drive from my house, but it was the closest place I could find that accepted patients without insurance.

The experience was a bit mixed. The staff at the clinic were generally nice, but there were times when I felt rushed during appointments. I think they were really busy since it was a community clinic, and sometimes I didn’t have the chance to ask all the questions I had. I was nervous about my health and the baby’s health, so it felt like I could have used a bit more time and attention.

I had regular check-ups every month, and I appreciated the ultrasounds and the chance to hear my baby’s heartbeat. Those moments were really special. Overall, I felt well cared for, but I also felt the strain of not having consistent healthcare access, especially since I was underinsured. It was a relief to have the care, but I often worried about how to manage the costs. 

Do you want to know more about any specific part of that experience?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I was primarily seeing a family nurse practitioner at the clinic for my prenatal care. She was really knowledgeable and did her best to make me feel comfortable during my visits. I appreciated that she took the time to explain things clearly and answer my questions, even if our appointments sometimes felt a bit rushed due to the high volume of patients.

I felt like she genuinely cared about my well-being and my baby’s health. There were moments when I could tell she was juggling a lot of responsibilities, but she always made an effort to connect with me. I remember feeling anxious during some appointments, and she would reassure me, which really helped.

However, since I was underinsured, I often worried about how much each visit would cost and whether I could afford the necessary tests and ultrasounds. That added a layer of stress to the experience, even though I was grateful for the care I was receiving.

If you're interested, I can share more about the specific services or support I received during my pregnancy.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I had prenatal appointments every month during my pregnancy, which I was really glad for. A typical visit usually started with me checking in at the front desk and then waiting in the exam room for the nurse to come in. They would take my vital signs, like my blood pressure and weight, and then ask me some questions about how I was feeling. 

After that, the nurse practitioner would come in to see me. She would start by asking about any concerns I had since our last appointment, and I always tried to jot down a few questions beforehand so I wouldn’t forget them. Then she would do a quick physical exam, listen to the baby’s heartbeat with a Doppler, and sometimes she would do an ultrasound if it was scheduled for that visit. Those were always the highlights for me because it felt so real to see my baby on the screen.

Towards the end of my pregnancy, we talked more about labor and delivery, what to expect, and made a birth plan. I really appreciated that she took time to explain what was happening with my body and the baby’s development. 

However, I did feel a bit rushed during some visits, especially when there were a lot of other patients waiting. I always wished for a bit more time to discuss my concerns. But overall, I felt supported and cared for, even if I sometimes left with lingering questions. Is there anything in particular about the appointments you would like me to elaborate on?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I didn’t experience any major health concerns or complications during my pregnancy, which I feel really fortunate about. The only thing I dealt with was some mild morning sickness in the first trimester, which wasn’t too severe. I had some days where I felt nauseous, but it usually passed after a few hours. 

Beyond that, I tried to stay active, but I was mainly sedentary due to my lifestyle and work. I was lucky that my blood pressure and other vital signs were always within the normal range throughout my pregnancy. I did have some worries about my mental health, especially with feeling isolated sometimes, but I had a good support system with my husband and family, which helped a lot. 

I did have a few moments of anxiety about being a first-time mom, but my nurse practitioner was always there to reassure me. She encouraged me to reach out if I felt overwhelmed or needed someone to talk to. Overall, while I was aware of the challenges, my pregnancy was uncomplicated, and I’m really grateful for that. 

Would you like to know more about how I managed my mental well-being during that time, or is there something else you’re curious about?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I’m not currently taking any medications or supplements. After my pregnancy, I didn’t feel the need for any specific medications, and I haven't been prescribed anything recently. I do try to eat a balanced diet when I can, but I know I could probably improve my nutrition overall. I sometimes take a multivitamin if I remember, but it’s not something I do consistently. 

I’ve been focusing more on managing my daily life and responsibilities, especially since I have a young child. I think I could benefit from some guidance on whether I should be taking any specific supplements or medications, but with my limited access to healthcare, it’s been tough to get that kind of advice. 

If you have any recommendations or guidance on that, I’d love to hear it!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancy, I tried to pay attention to my diet and nutrition, but it was a bit of a challenge given my busy lifestyle and the fact that cooking wasn't always easy with a lot going on. I made an effort to include more fruits and vegetables in my meals, and I focused on getting enough protein, especially since I knew it was important for my baby's development. 

I would often have eggs for breakfast or make smoothies with spinach, bananas, and yogurt. For lunch, I tried to have salads with some kind of protein—like chicken or beans—whenever I could. Dinner was usually a mix of whatever I could prepare quickly, which sometimes meant pasta or rice with veggies and a protein source. 

Snacking was another area where I tried to make better choices. I kept things like nuts, yogurt, and fruit on hand, but there were definitely times when I would grab something quick and not as healthy, especially if I was feeling tired or overwhelmed. 

I also drank a lot of water, which I was told was important, but I did have cravings for soda and sugary snacks now and then. I think the limited access to fresh produce in my area made it harder to stick to a really balanced diet. Overall, while I made an effort to eat well, I know I could have done better, especially with meal planning and preparation. 

Is there anything specific you'd like to know about my nutrition during pregnancy, or how it may have affected my health outcomes?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancy, my emotions were a bit of a mixed bag. There were definitely moments of joy and excitement, especially when I felt the baby move or saw the ultrasounds. Those were some of the highlights for me, and they made everything feel very real and special. However, I also experienced moments of anxiety and stress, particularly as a first-time mom.

There were days when I felt overwhelmed by the changes happening in my body and the responsibility of becoming a parent. I had some worries about how I would manage everything—being a good mom, handling the financial aspects, and just figuring out how to balance it all. The social isolation I felt at times also contributed to my emotional ups and downs. 

I often turned to my husband for support, and having him there made a big difference. We talked a lot about our hopes and fears, which helped me feel less alone. I also tried to connect with family and friends, even if it was just through phone calls or texts, because that support was really valuable.

There were times when I could have used more guidance on my mental health, especially when I was feeling particularly anxious. My nurse practitioner noticed I was a bit on edge during some visits, and she encouraged me to reach out if I needed to talk. I really appreciated that, but I sometimes felt hesitant to bring up my feelings because I didn’t want to seem like I was overreacting.

Overall, while I had my struggles, I was able to find moments of joy and connection, which helped me navigate the emotional challenges of pregnancy. If you're interested, I can share more about how I coped with those feelings or any specific strategies that helped me.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancy, my biggest support came from my husband. He was really involved and tried to help in any way he could, whether it was attending appointments with me or just being there to listen when I needed to talk about my feelings and concerns. I appreciated that he made an effort to understand what I was going through and to share in the excitement as well as the worries.

I also had support from my family, particularly my mom. She was a huge help, especially in the early days when I was adjusting to being pregnant. We would talk regularly, and she shared her experiences, which made me feel less alone. She also offered practical help, like cooking meals or helping with baby items. 

I did feel a bit isolated living in a rural area, and while I didn’t have many friends nearby, I tried to stay connected with some from high school through social media. I would reach out to them when I needed someone to talk to, but it wasn’t the same as having a close friend nearby. 

My nurse practitioner also played a supportive role. She encouraged me to reach out if I was feeling overwhelmed, which was comforting. I think having that professional support, combined with my family’s involvement, helped me feel more secure during my pregnancy. 

If you’d like, I can share more about specific ways that my husband and family supported me, or how I navigated the feelings of isolation.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancy, I did think quite a bit about my birth plan and what my preferences would be for delivery. Since my first delivery was uncomplicated, I felt a bit more confident this time around. I wanted to have a natural birth if everything went smoothly again, but I also understood that I needed to be flexible in case things didn’t go as planned.

I discussed my preferences with my nurse practitioner during my visits. I expressed that I wanted to try to labor at home as long as possible before heading to the hospital. I felt that being in a familiar environment might help me feel more comfortable. I also wanted to avoid unnecessary interventions if everything was progressing normally, but I understood that sometimes things can change unexpectedly.

I prepared for things like having music and a calming environment in the delivery room, as I thought that would help me relax. I was also clear about wanting my husband to be with me during the labor and delivery. His presence was really important to me, and I felt that having him there would provide the support I needed.

One thing I was a bit concerned about was how to manage pain during labor. I was open to discussing pain relief options with my healthcare team, but I hoped to try breathing techniques and movement first. I wanted to stay as active as possible during labor if I could.

Overall, I felt prepared, but I knew to keep an open mind about how everything might unfold. If you’re interested, I can share more about how I came to those decisions or any specific experiences I had while planning for my delivery.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancy, I relied on a few different sources of information to learn about pregnancy and childbirth. One of the main resources was my family nurse practitioner. She was really helpful in providing me with guidance during my appointments, and I appreciated her explanations and the materials she shared with me. 

I also turned to books about pregnancy and childbirth that I found at the local library. I read a couple of popular ones that offered insights into what to expect week by week, and I found them comforting. They helped me understand the changes happening in my body and gave me tips for labor and delivery. 

Additionally, I spent some time online researching pregnancy forums and websites. I found that reading about other women’s experiences and tips was really valuable. I joined a couple of online groups where moms shared their stories, and it was nice to connect with others who were going through similar experiences, even if it was just virtually. 

Social media was another source of information for me. I followed some accounts focused on pregnancy, parenting, and maternal health. They shared helpful tips, articles, and personal stories that resonated with me. 

However, I was sometimes cautious about the information I found online, as I wanted to ensure it was credible. I always tried to cross-reference what I read with the advice from my healthcare provider. 

If you’d like, I can tell you more about any specific topics I researched or how I felt about the information I found.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Managing the financial aspects of my pregnancy and preparing for my baby has definitely been a challenge. Since I’m underinsured and my husband’s income is not very high, we’ve had to be really careful about budgeting and planning for expenses.

I made sure to keep track of all the appointments and tests I needed during my pregnancy, and I tried to prioritize the ones that were essential for my health and the baby's health. We also had to think about costs related to delivery and what expenses would come after the baby arrived, like diapers, clothes, and other necessities.

To save money, we relied heavily on family and friends who offered to give us hand-me-downs or gifts for the baby. I felt grateful for that support because it helped ease some of the financial burden. We also looked for local resources, like community programs, that offered assistance for new parents or supplies for infants.

I tried to be proactive about finding deals or sales on baby items, and I often checked online or in local stores to compare prices. We also made a list of what we thought we would need versus what we could get by with for the first few months. 

Additionally, I’ve been keeping an eye on our monthly expenses to see where we could cut back, which has been necessary with my inconsistent work hours. It can be stressful worrying about how to provide for a new baby, but I’ve been focusing on making the best of what we have and relying on our support network when we can.

If you're interested, I can share more about specific strategies we’ve used to manage costs or how we’re preparing for the baby's arrival.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
My pregnancy did have an impact on my work and employment situation. As an administrative assistant, I tried to keep up with my job responsibilities during my pregnancy, but I faced some challenges. Since my hours have been inconsistent lately, it was a bit stressful trying to balance work and my health. I didn’t have a formal maternity leave since I was underinsured and my employer wasn’t required to offer one, so I had to be cautious about how I managed my time.

There were days when I felt really fatigued, especially in the first trimester when I was dealing with that mild morning sickness. I had to communicate with my supervisor about my needs, and I was fortunate that she was understanding. If I needed to leave early or take a break, I could usually work it out with her, which made things a little easier.

However, I also felt a lot of pressure to stay productive. I worried about how my time off would affect my job security, especially since we rely on my income, even if it’s not a lot. I also thought about how my performance might be judged during this time, so I tried to push through even when I wasn't feeling my best.

After my son was born, I took a short break to recover, but I had to return to work fairly quickly. It was tough to balance being a new mom and working, especially with the lack of available childcare in our area. My husband helped out as much as he could, but we were both juggling a lot. 

Overall, my pregnancy brought about a lot of stress when it came to work, and I often found myself worrying about how to manage everything. If you want, I can share more about how I navigated those challenges or any specific adjustments I made at work during my pregnancy.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancy, I definitely thought about the postpartum period and what it might be like after the baby arrives. I know that the weeks and months following delivery can be both exciting and challenging. My primary focus is to make sure I can take care of myself and my baby while also supporting my husband and adjusting to our new family dynamics.

I’ve talked to my husband about how we can share responsibilities after the baby comes. We plan to take turns with night feedings and diaper changes, so we can both get some rest. I also want to make sure I have a support system in place, particularly from my family, who have offered to help when they can. My mom has already said she’d be available to come and stay with us for a little while to help me adjust, which I really appreciate.

One thing I’ve been considering is how to take care of my mental health during the postpartum period. I know that a lot of new moms experience feelings of anxiety or sadness, and I want to be proactive about it. I plan to keep the lines of communication open with my husband and reach out to my nurse practitioner if I start feeling overwhelmed. I’d also like to find some local groups for new moms, but I'm not sure how accessible those will be in my area.

In terms of physical recovery, I’m aware that it’s important to take care of myself after delivery. I want to prioritize rest and nutrition, but I know that can be tricky with a newborn. I plan to stock up on healthy snacks and meals in advance, so I have easy options available when I’m too tired to cook.

We’re also trying to prepare for the financial aspects of postpartum life, like any additional expenses for baby supplies or healthcare visits. I want to make sure we’re budgeted for those, especially with my inconsistent work hours.

Overall, I’m feeling a bit anxious about the postpartum period, but I’m also hopeful. I want to enjoy those precious early moments with my baby while also being mindful of my own well-being. If you’d like, I can share more about specific worries or plans I have for postpartum care, or any resources I’m looking into.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
